ghts movement, eventually forcing the formal integration of American juvenile justice. Ward’s book reveals nearly a century of struggle to build a more democratic model of juvenile justice—an effort that succeeded in part, but ultimately failed to deliver black youth and community to liberal rehabilitative ideals. At once an inspiring story about the shifting boundaries of race, citizenship, and democracy in America and a crucial look at the nature of racial inequality, The Black Child Savers is a stirring account of the stakes and meaning of social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American children -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- History. 0aAfrican American childrenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDiscrimination in juvenile justice administration -- United States -- History. 0aDiscrimination in juvenile justice administrationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJuvenile courts -- United States -- History. 0aJuvenile courtszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration of -- United States -- History. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ajim crow, legal system, justice, law enforcement, democracy, race, racism, segregation, juvenile courts, discrimination, youth, delinquency, white savior, rehabilitation, criminalization, discipline, community, civil rights movement, integration, inclusion, frances joseph-gaudet, josephine ruffin, incarceration, labor, chain gang, activism, judges, probation officers, confinement, imprisonment, reform, innocence, nonfiction, history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226873190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97802